the legend has its own distinct drawn symbol. Each symbol_description must be unique \u2014 if you find yourself writing the same description for two or more consecutive rows, you have misread the legend and must look again. For LINE symbols: describe the line pattern precisely \u2014 solid/dashed/dotted/chain-dashed, thin/thick/heavy, and any decorations spaced along it (tick marks, letters like W or GAS, diagonal slashes, arrows). For POINT/ICON symbols: describe the outer shape (circle/square/rectangle/triangle), fill (hollow/solid black/half-filled), and any interior marks (cross, X, diagonal line, triangle, bowtie). Use the REFERENCE TABLE in the details field when you recognise a known symbol \u2014 match it and use the reference description. Ask yourself before writing each entry: 'Is this description unique and geometric? Could a reader draw exactly this symbol from my words alone without reading the label?'"}, {"title": "Copy the Label Verbatim", "instructions": "For the 'label' field, copy the exact text written next to the symbol on the drawing, preserving capitalisation and spacing. Do not paraphrase or abbreviate. If a symbol has no label, record label as '[UNLABELLED]'. If a label has no visible symbol, record symbol_description as '[NO SYMBOL]'."}, {"title": "Assign Category \u2014 MANDATORY for Every Entry", "instructions": "MANDATORY: 'category' is a required field for EVERY entry \u2014 NEVER null, NEVER omitted. If genuinely uncertain, use 'other'. PATTERN RULES \u2014 apply these in order: (1) 'cable': label contains any of TRENCH, CABLE, CONDUCTOR, OVERHEAD MAINS, UNDERGROUND MAINS, OVERHEAD LINE, DUCT, SPARE DUCT \u2014 examples: NEW LV TRENCH, EXISTING OVERHEAD MAINS, NEW UNDERGROUND MAINS, EXISTING UNDERGROUND CABLE, NEW OVERHEAD CONDUCTOR, REMOVE CONDUCTOR, REMOVE EXISTING OVERHEAD, STRING NEW OH CABLE. (2) 'equipment': label contains any of POLE, PILLAR, COLUMN, LANTERN, STREETLIGHT, SLCP, SL FLOOD, SL LANTERN, SL NIGHT WATCH, SHACKLE, JOINT, UGOH, HV ABS, HV USL, LV LINK, SWITCH, FUSE, METER, or label is a short equipment code (UGOH, IE 7.0 IA, IEB5, XXXXX treated as placeholder equipment code) \u2014 examples: EXISTING POLE, NEW POLE, REMOVE POLE, REPLACE POLE, EXISTING COLUMN, NEW COLUMN, EXISTING PILLAR, NEW PILLAR, EXISTING LANTERN, NEW LANTERN, REMOVE LANTERN, NEW SL FLOOD, EXISTING SL LANTERN, EXISTING SL NIGHT WATCH, NEW SLCP ZELL, EXISTING SLCP ZELL, REMOVE SL LANTERN, HV ABS (N/C), HV USL (N/C), EXISTING HV ABS CLOSE - REMOVE, NEW HV ABS CLOSE, EXISTING HV USL CLOSED, LV LINK (N/O), JOINT, END SHACKLE, UGOH. (3) 'substation': label contains SUBSTATION or KIOSK. (4) 'boundary': label contains EASEMENT, DEMARCATION, BOUNDARY, or LGA. (5) 'earthing': label is EARTHING or contains EARTH CONDUCTOR or EARTH ELECTRODE. (6) 'annotation': label is a dimension, callout, or arrow descriptor. (7) 'other': anything not matching above \u2014 includes TYPE 04 DUCT ARRANGEMENT, FOOTPATH, RMS ROAD, COMPACTED BACKFILL, POLYMERIC CABLE COVER, ROAD LEVEL, DUCT SPACING NTS, XXXXX (if not treating as equipment code). Apply pattern 1 first, then 2, then 3, then 4, then 5, then fall back to 'other'. NEVER leave category null."}, {"title": "Tag to Page Number", "instructions": "Tag each entry with the page number from the chunk metadata. If the same legend appears on multiple pages, record it once tagged to page 1. If different pages have different or updated legends, record separate entries per page."}, {"title": "Exhaustiveness Check \u2014 Do Not Stop Early", "instructions": "After completing your initial extraction pass, count the total number of entries extracted. Then re-scan the legend panel to verify you have not stopped at a section boundary. Many legends are divided into multiple sections (cables, equipment, boundaries, duct arrangements, miscellaneous) separated by horizontal rules or section headings \u2014 ensure every section has been processed. DUCT ARRANGEMENT SECTION: Some drawings include a separate duct arrangement cross-section diagram area at the bottom of the legend panel, often showing a schematic cross-section of underground ducts. This area contains its own rows with labels such as DUCT WITH EXISTING CABLE, DUCT WITH NEW CABLE, NEW TRENCH, REMOVE CABLE, REMOVE DUCT & CABLE, REMOVE DUCT, SPARE DUCT, EARTHING, DUCT SPACING NTS \u2014 these are regular legend entries and MUST be extracted like any other row. Assign them category 'cable' for duct/cable/trench entries, 'earthing' for EARTHING, and 'other' for annotations like DUCT SPACING NTS. If you see a cross-section diagram in the legend area, always extract every labelled row from it. If the legend contains 10 or more visible rows but you have extracted fewer than 5 entries, you have missed most of the legend and must re-scan. Also verify: (1) every entry has the 'category' field present and is never null; (2) no entry has extra fields beyond the four required (page, symbol_description, label, category) \u2014 any other field name is a violation; (3) the 'label' field contains the exact verbatim text from the drawing, not a paraphrase. If any entry fails these checks, correct it before returning the result."}]}], "instructional_sub_steps": null}, "documents_folder": "/documents/NRL15205-85 - Exp/", "total_files": 1, "extractions": [{"filename": "A524058_NRL15205_RETIC_NOTES.pdf", "filepath": "", "document_type": "Reticulation Notes", "document_category": "Site Plan", "input_text_quality": "none", "document_quality": "chunked-image", "page_size": "A3", "requires_chunking": true, "chunk_strategy": "quadrant-split", "estimated_chunks": 4, "actual_chunks_processed": 4, "process_step_name": "Extract Drawing Legend", "total_sections": 4, "relevant_sections": 4, "raw_text_from_chunks": "[top-left, p1, seq1] D\nC\nB\nN\nA\n1\n2\nSITE PLAN\nSCALE 1:1000\nExisting\nDwelling\n3X0463\n03\nPole 4\nRemove LV overhead mains from Pole 3\nInstall LV UGOH on Pole 4\nExtend 240mm2 4 Core Al XLPE cable to Pillar 400355\n4